sentence_chunk: I belong to a humble middle class family. I was born in Mumbai, India. My father owned a business and my mother is a homemaker. I have an elder sister who is also a software engineer. I did most of my primary, secondary schooling from Mumbai and since then, I’ve been staying far from home due to education or work. I’m currently 26 years old studying in the United states with my second home in Sunnyvale, California. I currently have F1 -OPT work authorization to work for any employer in the United States until my visa expires by 2028. I’m open to H1-B sponsorship in future but won’t be needing any kind of sponsorship to start working. I am an Asian hetrosexual man with a minor disability and I won’t require any kind of special accommodations and can work better than a regular person. I do not have any political background and I do not have any military experience nor any relationships involved in government whatsoever.

I am open to relocation at my own expense. The influence of culture on the experiences and aspirations of youngsters growing up in India, particularly in the profession of engineering, is substantial. I was born and raised in one of India's most developed provinces, Maharashtra. Academic excellence and professional success are highly valued in our culture. Children in my society are frequently pushed by their parents and educators to work diligently in school and to seek occupations in fields that are well regarded and have a strong and secure earning potential, such as engineering. As a result of the circumstance that I come from a household with little financial resources, my parents did not deviate from the conventional parenting styles that are common in my community. India is renowned for its contributions to science and technology, including mathematics, astronomy, and engineering, dating back to ancient times. This rich history of innovation and problem-solving fostered a culture in which I was exposed to and encouraged to pursue a career in technology and engineering from an early age. There are numerous engineering institutes and universities in Maharashtra, making it comparatively straightforward for children to pursue engineering. The state of Maharashtra has a strong tradition in the field of technology, since it is home to numerous large engineering firms and industrial organizations, and as a result, it has a high demand for engineers.
In light of these considerations, I deemed it prudent to study engineering to innovate and improve

the systems and infrastructure that support our daily lives, while simultaneously establishing a solid, respectable career to support my family. Everyone has an epiphany in life that becomes a pivotal moment. When I was pursuing my undergraduate degree in Electrical and Computer Engineering, I had one such experience. The world craves innovative methods that can transform data into knowledge-rich treasure troves, bridging the gap between data and information. Today, in the era of technology-enhanced consumerism, every aspect of our everyday activities is captured in digital packets, which are subsequently analyzed and used to develop a company's marketing approach. Due to the growing connectedness and availability of technology, the quantity and variety of data collected by enterprises today are astounding. The issue with amassing a large volume of data is employing an efficient technique to access that data, regardless of the number of queries or the size of the data. In 2016, while anxiously awaiting the results of my JEE advanced entrance exam, I encountered this predicament. The examination is one of the most anticipated events on a national scale. As expected, a system failure caused by massive user requests prevented hundreds of hopefuls, including myself, from accessing their results for several hours.

This experience made me understand that it is not enough to merely modernize infrastructure with increasingly reliable technology; there will be a need for a mediator capable of constructing super-efficient pipelines to prevent inconvenience and save precious time. I was looking for a program that builds a strong foundation between people, technology, and the organization and handles most of the business-related operations, like strategic decision-making, more efficiently. That’s how I got to know about the Master of Science in Management Information Systems (MS-MIS). Information systems (IS) is a field that is reaping massive rewards all at once. It started with manual frameworks like customer databases and catalogs and has progressed to high-level speculation like predictive data mining. Fast movements in the field of information systems have left me stupefied. Having worked in the same domain for years and managing various endeavors, I accept that I have acquired congruous information and its applications and feel that I am prepared to push ahead in the field of Information Systems. To stay current on developments in this field and to prepare myself for the industry's regarded rules, I would like to pursue a graduate program in

information systems from your highly regarded university. I am aware that a dynamic course like MIS not only needs abnegation or austerity but also pragmatic exposure. At my tender age, I have been equipping myself to burn the midnight oil. At the age of 16, I scored in the top 0.01 percentile of nearly 2 million applicants nationwide in the JEE Advanced 2016 entrance exam. The same year itself, I joined Indian Institute of Technology Kanpur (IIT Kanpur) as a sophomore enrolled in the BTech (EECS) program. Curriculum involving preliminary courses like applied mathematics, probability statistics, and linear algebra helped me learn about different tools required for statistical analysis, such as regression analysis and differential equations, which came in handy in the device modeling part of my thesis research work. In 2018, I was the only student from my branch of 140 to land a GE Healthcare internship. This 3-month internship focused on infant care solutions. During this internship, I had the opportunity to lead a data-driven project focused on improving customer segmentation and predicting churn within an e-commerce sales dataset. This experience allowed me to combine my technical expertise in data science and machine learning with real-world business challenges, driving meaningful insights and outcomes for the company.

The project revolved around customer behavior analysis, where I applied machine learning techniques such as k-means clustering and logistic regression to segment customers based on their purchasing patterns and identify those at risk of churn. By analyzing the customer-product dataset, I helped GE develop more targeted marketing strategies, which resulted in more personalized customer experiences and ultimately improved retention rates. In addition to segmentation, I also employed collaborative filtering techniques to recommend products to customers, thereby enhancing cross-sell and up-sell opportunities. These machine learning models were built using Python and libraries like Scikit-learn and Pandas, leveraging both structured and unstructured data to generate actionable insights. Another key aspect of the internship involved sentiment analysis on product and customer reviews. By developing natural language processing (NLP) models, I was able to achieve a 76% accuracy rate in analyzing customer sentiments, which helped GE better understand customer perceptions and adapt their product offerings

accordingly. I used Python’s NLTK and TextBlob libraries for this task, which facilitated the extraction of meaningful insights from large text corpora. The project was completed 30% earlier than anticipated, thanks to my implementation of agile methodologies and effective sprint management. I coordinated with cross-functional teams, regularly reporting progress and adapting the project roadmap based on stakeholder feedback. This proactive approach not only accelerated the delivery but also improved the overall efficiency of business operations by 5%. This internship sharpened my skills in applying machine learning algorithms to real-world business problems and gave me a strong foundation in handling large datasets, performing predictive analytics, and generating data-driven insights. My ability to work across the entire machine learning pipeline—from data collection and cleaning to model building and deployment—aligns with the core competencies required in data engineering and software engineering roles. One of my other projects was to construct hardware to validate sonography-detected newborn movements. I surveyed pregnant mothers at different stages of pregnancy to get first-hand data on fetal movement. This gave us statistics and end-user input on our goods.

Finding the desired signal in the dataset was a monumental undertaking. I used FFT analysis and a band-pass filtering module to get the appropriate fetal movement signal. In a short time, I constructed a prototype circuit that could stimulate fetal movement with 73% accuracy. Based on the engineer's input, my prototype passed the sonography equipment validation criteria. Due to the short term of my internship, doing sonography tests on pregnant women would have been expensive and time-consuming. So I plunged an analog clock into jelly to resemble a newborn in the womb. Analog watch ticking can be considered to indicate a baby's heart rate; jelly can be amniotic fluid. This method enabled me to conduct tests with results that resembled radiography reports. At IIT Kanpur, I was actively involved in student activities and extracurriculars. As a member of the fine arts club, I painted the walls of our Olympic-sized swimming pool in my first year.
Aside from that, I was actively involved in organizing our yearly cultural festival, "Antaragni". As the manager of our retail location for the

festival, I used aggressive pricing and marketing tactics to improve sales compared to earlier iterations. Even though these experiences taught me great lessons in teamwork, tenacity, and the fundamentals of business intelligence, the most essential lesson I learned was the necessity of maintaining balance. I became distracted from my academic work due to all of my time-consuming obligations, which affected my grades. I, therefore, do not think that my undergraduate performance accurately reflects my academic abilities. Despite having a mediocre undergraduate record, I managed to gain a lucrative internship opportunity at GE by undergoing a rigorous system of aptitude and interpersonal assessment. My ability to balance academic and extracurricular pursuits while pursuing a master's degree has allowed me to consistently achieve a high GPA of 3.5 in a highly competitive academic environment, which is a better indicator of my ability to succeed in an academic setting while simultaneously managing the position of Teaching Assistantship and volunteer work for "Prayas". In 2019, I was accepted into a dual-degree master’s program based on my academic achievements and project portfolio. During this time, I had the opportunity to work closely with Prof. Dr. Amit Verma for 14 months on a research project focused on VLSI and semiconductor technologies, where we aimed to find more economical and scalable alternatives to traditional data storage systems, such as hard disks and memory units. Our goal was to significantly reduce the high investment costs associated with these technologies by exploring new materials with the potential to revolutionize data storage. My role in this project was to research and develop a machine-learning-driven approach to map the physical behavior of vanadium dioxide (VO2), a material with strong potential as a substitute for conventional memory hardware.

I employed machine learning algorithms, including regression models, to create a predictive mathematical model that could simulate the material's behavior under varying electro-thermal conditions. This involved training the model on experimental data to predict the material's phase changes—key to determining its viability as a storage medium—at different temperatures and voltages. To improve prediction accuracy and refine the model, I applied neural networks and experimented with feature engineering to better capture the nonlinear relationships between electro-thermal thresholds and material properties.

This approach was necessary because traditional regression models struggled to capture the intricate interactions between temperature, voltage, and current, all of which influence the material’s phase transitions. The first crucial step in building the neural network was data preprocessing. The experimental data collected from tests on VO2 included various features like temperature, voltage, and current, all of which had different ranges. To ensure the model could efficiently learn from the data, I applied data normalization, scaling the input features so they were within a uniform range. This was essential to help the neural network avoid issues with uneven gradients and allowed for faster convergence during training. Additionally, I performed feature engineering, where I created interaction terms that represented the electro-thermal interplay more accurately. These new features helped the model account for the complex physics underlying the material's behavior. When designing the neural network, I opted for a feedforward architecture with multiple hidden layers. The input layer consisted of the scaled temperature, voltage, and current features. I included two hidden layers, each with ReLU (Rectified Linear Unit) activation functions.

ReLU was chosen for its efficiency in modeling non-linear relationships and its ability to address the vanishing gradient problem, which can arise during backpropagation. This activation function enabled the network to learn complex patterns from the data, which was critical for predicting VO2’s phase transitions at different electro-thermal thresholds. The output layer used a linear activation function to predict the continuous variable representing the phase change of the material. To train the neural network, I used the mean squared error (MSE) as the loss function. MSE was ideal for this project because it provided a clear metric for evaluating the difference between the model’s predicted phase behavior and the actual experimental results. To optimize the model, I applied the Adam optimizer (Adaptive Moment Estimation), which is particularly effective for problems with noisy gradients. Adam allowed for efficient gradient-based optimization, speeding up the learning process and improving the model’s accuracy. Given the limited dataset, preventing overfitting was a significant concern. Overfitting occurs when a model becomes too complex and learns the noise in the training data, which reduces its ability to generalize to new data. To address this, I employed dropout regularization, where a random subset of neurons in the hidden layers was ignored during each training epoch.
This forced the neural network to learn more robust

patterns in the data, rather than memorizing specific features. Additionally, I used early stopping, monitoring the validation loss during training and halting the process once the model’s performance on the validation set ceased to improve. This technique further ensured that the model did not overfit to the training data. The model’s performance was also heavily influenced by hyperparameter tuning. Through trial and error, I experimented with different learning rates, ultimately finding an optimal rate that balanced speed and accuracy. I also tuned the batch size, selecting a smaller batch size due to the limited dataset, which allowed for more frequent updates to the model weights. Additionally, I adjusted the number of neurons in the hidden layers to find the ideal configuration for capturing the material’s non-linear behavior. After training, the model was evaluated using various metrics, including mean absolute error (MAE) and R-squared (R²), to ensure its predictions were reliable. The neural network achieved over 60% accuracy in predicting vanadium dioxide’s phase transitions, a significant improvement over linear models. This result demonstrated that machine learning, particularly neural networks, could effectively model the behavior of materials like VO2 across different electro-thermal conditions.

By applying these neural network techniques, I was able to develop a robust predictive model that captured the complex interactions of electro-thermal properties, contributing valuable insights to the field of data storage technologies. This project not only showcased my ability to apply machine learning in a practical, research-based setting but also highlighted my skills in data preprocessing, model optimization, and performance evaluation. Despite facing significant challenges due to limited computational resources, I optimized the model and achieved over 60% accuracy in predicting the material’s behavior. This was a crucial step in validating the potential of vanadium dioxide as a future alternative to traditional memory technologies, especially for large-scale data centers and storage units. Throughout this project, I gained hands-on experience in Python programming, applying data analytics, and implementing machine learning techniques in a research setting. Additionally, I developed skills in mathematical modeling and working with complex datasets, which required a deep understanding of material science and data processing. By translating physical behaviors into data models, I was able to bridge the gap between

hardware research and software engineering, making the results applicable to the broader field of data storage optimization. This research not only enhanced my technical skills but also taught me how to approach complex, data-intensive problems in innovative ways, making my experience highly relevant to roles in software development, particularly in areas related to machine learning, data-driven applications, and system optimization. Through this project, I developed a deep understanding of how software solutions can be applied to advance hardware technology, making me a well-rounded candidate for software engineering roles that require both development and data analysis expertise. My accomplished masters-level research project serves as an excellent example of my aptitude and analytical thinking. Given that I could work in uncharted territory like research and overcome all the hurdles in a brief period of time, my successful thesis defense in front of a panel of seasoned researchers and academics gave me confidence. My inquisitiveness didn’t end there. During my time as a Software Engineer at the Center for Development of Advanced Computing (C-DAC) starting from August 2021 till February 2023, I had the opportunity to work on several key projects that allowed me to deepen my expertise in backend development, particularly in the context of microservices architecture and enterprise-level systems. My primary focus was on developing scalable, efficient microservices using Java and the Spring Boot framework, which significantly enhanced the performance and maintainability of the systems I worked on. One of the most impactful aspects of my role was leading the development of a suite of RESTful microservices. These microservices were designed to support the internal infrastructure of the organization by seamlessly integrating various web services.

The architecture followed the principles of modular design, allowing different components of the system to function independently while still maintaining a coherent flow of data between them. By utilizing Spring Boot, I was able to simplify the configuration and deployment process, reducing code complexity by 20%. This resulted in a more streamlined and maintainable codebase, which greatly improved the efficiency of the development team. The backend systems I worked on required robust API development. I created and managed multiple custom endpoints, designed to meet specific business requirements. These APIs facilitated communication

between internal services and external clients, ensuring that data was transmitted securely and efficiently. Using Spring Boot’s REST framework, I implemented JWT-based authentication to ensure secure data transmission across the microservices. This not only improved the system’s security but also made it easier to manage user sessions and authorization, critical in an enterprise environment where data integrity and security are paramount. Another major focus of my work at C-DAC was database optimization. Many of the systems I worked on relied heavily on Oracle RDBMS for data storage and retrieval. Over time, I observed that some of the existing SQL queries were becoming bottlenecks, slowing down the overall system performance. To address this, I optimized several complex SQL queries, improving query performance by 35%. This optimization involved reworking query structures, indexing strategies, and applying advanced SQL tuning techniques to ensure faster and more efficient data retrieval. The result was a notable improvement in the responsiveness of the system, which was especially critical for applications that handled large datasets and required real-time performance. In addition to my individual contributions, I also had the opportunity to mentor a team of three junior engineers.

This aspect of my role was incredibly rewarding, as it allowed me to share my knowledge and experience while fostering a collaborative environment. I worked closely with the team to ensure they understood the core principles of microservices development, API design, and database management. Together, we were able to increase the efficiency of our development processes, ultimately boosting project outcomes by 20%. My mentorship not only helped the team transition more smoothly into their roles but also contributed to a more cohesive and productive engineering unit. Throughout my time at C-DAC, I employed various software development best practices, including design patterns and Agile methodologies. I was actively involved in code reviews, which helped maintain a high standard of code quality across the team. These practices ensured that the systems we built were not only efficient and scalable but also easy to maintain and extend over time. In summary, my experience at C-DAC was instrumental in honing my skills in backend development and microservices architecture. I gained significant hands-on experience with Java, Spring Boot, RESTful APIs, and database optimization, all while working in a collaborative, team-oriented environment. The work I did there

laid a strong foundation for my career as a software developer, equipping me with the tools and knowledge to tackle complex, large-scale systems in future roles. At that point in my career, I had spent most of my time putting in a great deal of effort and hard work to conquer every quagmire in my life. Be it being shunned for being differently abled or carving a divergent path in the form of MIS, "Panglossian" isn’t just a word in my dictionary. This demonstrates my commitment to my aspirations and objectives. To be able to carry out what I love doing the most, I applied for an MS-MIS from the University of Arizona. In the last few years, the US has dominated the world as one of the most popular destinations for students to pursue higher education from all over the globe. Eller school of the University of Arizona is ranked as the top-rated institution in the United States for a master’s degree. The MS-MIS at University of Arizona offered unique strength of technical expertise through database management, data networks with a quantitative edge through business analytics, and data mining. This has ameliorated my proficiency and helped me become an invaluable asset to any organizations in the field of Information Technology and Engineering. In the Data Mining project at the University of Arizona, I had the opportunity to lead the design and development of a data infrastructure that processed large-scale unstructured data and transformed it into actionable insights.

This project required a deep understanding of data mining techniques, cloud computing, and data engineering best practices to build a scalable solution that could handle real-time data ingestion and analysis. The primary focus of the project was to establish a centralized data lake on Amazon S3 to store data from multiple sources, including video metadata from the YouTube Data API. This data was vast and unstructured, requiring significant preprocessing and transformation before it could be used for any meaningful analysis. To handle the large volume and variety of data, I architected a pipeline that would ingest, process, and structure the data for downstream analytics. For the data ingestion, I utilized AWS Lambda functions to automate the retrieval of data from the YouTube API. Lambda’s serverless architecture allowed the pipeline to scale effortlessly, processing data in real-time as it was retrieved. The flexibility of Amazon S3 as a storage solution made it ideal for handling the different formats and types of data we were working with, ensuring that we had a centralized repository for all incoming data. Once the data

was ingested, I used AWS Glue to transform the raw, unstructured data into a more structured format that could be analyzed more efficiently. Glue’s ETL (Extract, Transform, Load) capabilities allowed me to define the transformation steps needed to clean and organize the data, including handling missing values, normalizing formats, and mapping relationships between different data points. The transformed data was stored in Amazon Athena, which allowed us to perform SQL-like queries on the structured data stored in S3. A significant challenge in this project was ensuring that the data pipeline could handle the ingestion and transformation of massive amounts of data without performance bottlenecks. To address this, I applied parallel processing and distributed computing techniques using AWS Glue’s built-in Spark engine. This enabled the pipeline to process large datasets in parallel, significantly improving the speed and efficiency of data transformation operations. For the data analysis component, we focused on extracting insights from the transformed data using a variety of data mining techniques. One of the key tasks involved identifying patterns in YouTube user engagement data, such as identifying trending topics, analyzing video viewership patterns, and understanding user behavior over time. I employed algorithms such as k-means clustering to segment users based on their viewing habits and decision trees to classify videos into different categories based on metadata and engagement statistics. Additionally, I integrated sentiment analysis to assess the sentiment of user comments on videos, providing a deeper understanding of how audiences responded to specific types of content.

By leveraging natural language processing (NLP) techniques, I was able to build models that classified comments as positive, negative, or neutral, giving us a clearer picture of audience reception and engagement. One of the highlights of the project was its ability to generate real-time insights. By building the pipeline on AWS, I ensured that the data processing was fast and efficient, allowing us to analyze incoming data in near real-time. This was particularly valuable for identifying trends as they emerged, such as detecting spikes in viewership or engagement related to viral content. The use of AWS Athena and Amazon QuickSight further allowed us to visualize these insights, creating dynamic dashboards that stakeholders could use to monitor key metrics without needing advanced technical knowledge. Throughout the project, I gained hands-on experience with cloud-native technologies and big data processing, learning how to manage data lakes, automate data pipelines, and

implement machine learning algorithms for pattern detection and analysis. I also honed my skills in Python, SQL, and distributed computing, all of which are critical to roles in software development and data engineering. The ability to design scalable data architectures and develop pipelines that convert raw data into actionable insights is a valuable skill set that I carry into all of my software development and data-related roles. As a Database Architect for the University of Arizona Library live project, I was responsible for designing and implementing a robust database system that met the complex needs of a large academic institution. This project was particularly challenging because it required the integration of numerous data sources, each with its own unique set of requirements and use cases. My role involved gathering business requirements, designing a conceptual and logical data model, and building a physical database that could support both the operational and analytical needs of the library. The first step in this project was conducting consultations with clients and stakeholders to gather detailed business requirements. These discussions were crucial in understanding the various entities involved, such as books, authors, publishers, students, and faculty, as well as the relationships between these entities. Based on these requirements, I designed a 40-entity complex conceptual data model that could accurately represent the data structure. The model was created with scalability in mind, ensuring that as the library grew and its data needs evolved, the database could handle the increased complexity without major overhauls.

Once the conceptual model was approved, I moved on to creating a logical schema that reduced redundancy and optimized data storage. The challenge was to design a system that could store vast amounts of data efficiently while maintaining data integrity. By using normalization techniques, I was able to minimize data duplication and ensure that the database design adhered to best practices for relational databases. This streamlined design resulted in a 30% reduction in redundancy, making the database more efficient and easier to maintain. For the physical design of the database, I used SQL Server Management Studio (SSMS) to implement the logical model into a fully functioning database. I created tables, indexes, and constraints to ensure data integrity, and used PL/SQL to write the necessary stored procedures and triggers. This allowed for automation of common

tasks, such as updating records, ensuring referential integrity, and enforcing business rules. One of the most critical aspects of the project was building an ETL (Extract, Transform, Load) pipeline to handle the movement of data from various sources into the central database. I used SQL Server Integration Services (SSIS) to design and implement this pipeline, which was responsible for transforming and loading data into the system. The pipeline incorporated error handling and logging mechanisms to ensure that any issues with data quality or integrity were quickly identified and resolved. By automating the data loading process, we were able to reduce the manual effort required and ensure that the data was always up to date. To further enhance the system’s reliability, I integrated SQL Server Agent to schedule regular data loads and maintenance tasks. This allowed us to automate critical operations, such as backups and updates, ensuring that the system remained operational with minimal downtime. The combination of automated ETL processes and scheduled tasks improved the overall efficiency and reliability of the database system. One of the key objectives of the project was to bring the library’s data services in-house, which was estimated to save the university $40,000 in operational costs. By consolidating data from various external vendors into a single, internally managed system, the library was able to gain more control over its data, improve access to information, and reduce dependency on third-party services.

This also enhanced the reliability of the system, as the library could now directly manage its data infrastructure, ensuring faster response times and more tailored solutions for its users. Throughout the project, I applied database design principles and best practices in data modeling, ETL pipeline development, and SQL programming. I also gained valuable experience in client consultation and translating business requirements into technical solutions. My work on this project provided me with hands-on experience in designing scalable, efficient database systems and developing robust data pipelines, which are critical skills for software development, particularly in roles involving data engineering, database management, and backend systems development. Academic coursework at University of Arizona, Eller College challenges students to the limit. One of the courses was designed in such a way for students that we had an opportunity to work on a live project working alongside clients for the Spring 2024 semester ( January 2024 to May 2024). I worked with a local client, a real

estate property management company, Cortland Las Casas. During my time as a Full Stack Developer at Cortland Las Casas, a startup based in Tucson, AZ, I had the unique opportunity to work on developing scalable, user-friendly applications that directly impacted the company’s operations. This role allowed me to blend my skills in both frontend and backend development, giving me hands-on experience in building and deploying web applications from the ground up. One of the key projects I worked on was designing and implementing a microservices-based backend architecture using JWT (JSON Web Token) authentication. The goal was to create a secure, scalable backend that could handle multiple services while maintaining a centralized authentication mechanism. By using JWT, I ensured that the system was secure and that user authentication could be managed in a decentralized manner, making it easier to scale the application as new services were added. This architecture allowed different components of the system to communicate seamlessly, ensuring that user sessions were handled securely and efficiently across services. For the backend development, I primarily worked with the MERN stack (MongoDB, Express, React, NodeJS). On the backend, I focused on building RESTful APIs using NodeJS and Express, ensuring that the APIs were well-documented and easy to integrate with the frontend. I utilized MongoDB as the database, taking advantage of its scalability and flexibility, which were crucial for a startup environment where the application needed to grow rapidly in terms of both data volume and complexity.

By building asynchronous, non-blocking APIs, I optimized the backend for handling concurrent requests, ensuring smooth performance even under heavy user loads. On the frontend, I leveraged React to build a monolithic frontend application that communicated with the microservices-based backend. I made extensive use of React Router and the Context API to manage state across the application, ensuring that user data and sessions were maintained seamlessly as users navigated through different parts of the site. This approach allowed for a more dynamic user experience, improving both the performance and usability of the frontend. Additionally, I employed Tailwind CSS to design a responsive, visually appealing UI that catered to the startup’s user base. By optimizing the frontend using stateful React components, I was able to ensure that the application performed well even on lower-end devices, providing a smooth experience across different platforms. To ensure that the application was reliable and easy to maintain, I implemented CI/CD pipelines

using GitHub Actions. This automated the testing and deployment process, significantly reducing the time needed to deploy new features or updates. By setting up automated testing, I ensured that any changes made to the codebase were thoroughly vetted before being deployed, minimizing the risk of bugs or issues in production. This was crucial in a startup environment where development cycles were short, and the ability to quickly roll out new features without compromising on quality was key to the project’s success. Throughout my time at Cortland Las Casas, I worked in an Agile development environment, collaborating closely with other developers and stakeholders to ensure that the product met the evolving needs of the business. We held regular scrum meetings to prioritize tasks and ensure that the most critical features were delivered on time. This iterative development process allowed us to rapidly prototype, test, and deploy features, adapting quickly to feedback and making improvements in real time. This experience was invaluable in deepening my understanding of full stack development, from designing scalable backend systems to creating intuitive, responsive frontends. It also enhanced my skills in API development, authentication mechanisms, and cloud-native deployment, all of which are critical in modern software development. My work at Cortland Las Casas provided me with the technical and collaborative skills needed to excel in software development roles, especially those focusing on backend architecture, microservices, and cloud deployment.

During my academic journey at University of Arizona, I had the opportunity to work under Dr. Hoover as Graduate Research Assistant since January 2024. With all the hard work, dedication and perseverance, I managed to receive an academic scholarship of full tuition waiver. As a Graduate Research Assistant at the Hoover Research Lab at the University of Arizona, I had the opportunity to work on projects that combined advanced artificial intelligence techniques with robust data engineering processes. My role involved a mixture of backend development, machine learning, and data pipeline orchestration, which greatly enhanced my technical skill set, particularly in the areas of AI, big data, and cloud computing. One of the most significant aspects of my work was the development of a Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) pipeline to deploy a private AI service. The goal of this project was to enhance traditional language models by integrating a

retrieval mechanism to provide more contextually relevant responses, improving the model's output accuracy. For this, I leveraged the LLAMA 3.2-3B model, a state-of-the-art, transformer-based language model. The integration of FAISS (Facebook AI Similarity Search) allowed the system to efficiently retrieve relevant documents from millions of records based on user queries. By clustering the data and optimizing similarity search, we ensured that the AI service delivered precise, contextually appropriate results, even when operating on large datasets. In addition to my work on the AI service, I was responsible for designing and implementing dimensional data models using a Snowflake schema. This involved processing large-scale datasets, often comprising 8 millions of rows, to create a scalable and efficient data architecture. To handle this volume of data, I utilized PySpark, a powerful API for large-scale data processing, allowing me to perform distributed computations across multiple nodes. This parallelized approach significantly improved the throughput and reduced the latency of data transformations, ensuring the data models could efficiently handle the demands of real-time analytics. To further streamline the data pipeline, I migrated the ETL (Extract, Transform, Load) process to Apache Airflow, which allowed for more sophisticated workflow management. By creating Directed Acyclic Graphs (DAGs), I was able to orchestrate various stages of the data pipeline, ensuring that tasks were completed in the correct sequence and that errors were handled gracefully.

This migration not only improved the reliability of the pipeline but also provided better monitoring and error tracking, essential for handling complex workflows. I deployed the entire system using Docker, which ensured that the environment was consistent across development and production, reducing the potential for deployment issues and improving the overall flexibility of the system. An equally important part of my role involved working on data visualization. I developed interactive dashboards using Power BI, which allowed researchers and stakeholders to generate insights from the processed data without needing in-depth SQL knowledge. This no-code approach reduced the dependency on SQL for analysis and enabled faster decision-making. The dashboards provided a user-friendly interface to track key metrics and trends, facilitating data-driven decisions without the need for constant technical intervention. Throughout the project, I applied software engineering best practices, including design patterns, solid principles, and modular coding techniques. These practices ensured that the

systems I developed were not only scalable but also maintainable in the long run. My experience with cloud platforms like AWS, along with tools like Apache Spark, Airflow, and Docker, gave me a deep understanding of how to build robust, scalable systems for processing and analyzing big data in cloud environments. This experience as a Graduate Research Assistant allowed me to sharpen my skills in backend engineering, data architecture, and AI model deployment, all of which are critical in the software development landscape.
